[1;31mView Command Keys         [1;31mCommands[0m

View uses regular expressions for searching. Sounds simple, right. Just
regular old expressions. But if you have never used regular expressions
before, they can be a little intimidating. So here is a quick primer on
regular expressions. If you already know regular expressions, you can
skip this section.

The "." is a wildcard character that matches any single character. For
example, "c.t" would match "cat", "cot", "cut", etc. The "*" is a
quantifier that matches zero or more of the preceding character. For
example, "ca*t" would match "ct", "cat", "caat", "caaat", etc. The "+"
is a quantifier that matches one or more of the preceding character.
For example, "ca+t" would match "cat", "caat", "caaat", etc. The "?"
is a quantifier that matches zero or one of the preceding character.
For example, "ca?t" would match "ct" and "cat". The "^" is an anchor
that matches the beginning of a line. For example, "^cat" would match
any line that starts with "cat". The "$" is an anchor that matches
the end of a line. For example, "cat$" would match any line that ends
with "cat". The "|" is an alternation operator that matches either
the expression before or after it. For example, "cat|dog" would match
either "cat" or "dog". The parentheses are used for grouping. For
example, "(cat|dog)s" would match either "cats" or "dogs".

Admittedly, this is a very brief introduction to regular expressions.
There are many more features and nuances to regular expressions that
are not covered here. But this should be enough to get you started
with using regular expressions in View. One of the best sources of
information on regular expressions is a website named
https://regex101.com. It has a great interactive regex tester and a 
comprehensive reference for regular expression syntax.

Other than that, the navigation in view is fairly straightforward.
You can use the arrow keys to scroll up and down one line at a time,
use page up and down to page through the document, or use the Scroll
wheel on your mouse. For the seasoned professionals, the standard h,
j, k, and l keys also work for moving around in the document. There
are also various other ways to move around in view, by going to
specific line numbers or searching for all matches with extended
regular expressions.

